@NODE "Version2.5" "V2.5 (Released on 11-Dec-2003):"

   For Version 2.5, the following enhancements/bug fixes were
   made:

   * Rewrote the Memory management code so that AmigaTalk will actually
     free the memory used during program execution.  AmigaTalk still uses 
     a reference-counting scheme to keep track of active Objects, but the 
     original Little-Smalltalk code never freed anything when the program
     was exiting (if you're lucky, it would actually free Objects during
     execution, but most of the time it would stick unused Objects onto
     free lists).  The program will check that you have enough memory
     available to run the program (against the *TableSize ToolTypes in
     the Icon).

   * Added a better way to keep track of Intuition, DosFlags, BOOPSITags
     DataTypeTags & PrinterTags.  Originally, they were subclassed as
     Dictionaries, which made them much larger than necessary.  With the
     new system, these Tags & Flags are stored in the AmigaTalk:CodeLib/
     directory as files, which are opened & read in when you instantiate the
     appropriate Class.  This saves over 20MB of memory & a lot of loading
     time at the start of the program.  The only drawback is that the files
     no longer contain comments as to what the various Flags & Tags are for
     (better buy the RKM or get help from someone that has one!).

   * Added ATalkConfig to the distribution so that you can configure
     the program to your tastes.

  *  According to page 14 of @{I}"A Little Smalltalk"@{UI} by Tim Budd: @{B}
     "Within the array list the leading pound sign on symbols and arrays
     can be eliminated."@{UB}  This behavior is no longer true for statements
     entered in the Command Line String Gadget or in Script files.  By allowing
     lowerCase variables in Arrays & ByteArrays, we can now just place
     variables in Arrays or ByteArrays & AmigaTalk will perform the 
     substitution(s) necessary to generate correct code.  The Parser can be
     made to do the same thing, but the Interpreter does not know how to
     find instance variables or context variables in order to perform the
     substitution(s).  This is not really a bug, but there is now a deviation
     between the Parser & what you can do with script files & the Command String
     Gadget!  @{B}Also, be aware that variables in ByteArrays MUST be Integers
     or Characters;@{UB} otherwise you will see an error message generated!
      
   * Added the @{" GTBTranslator " LINK "GTBTranslator.guide/Main"} program to the distribution.

   * Added two new menu items to the @{B}PROJECT@{UB} Menu to allow the addition
     & removal of User Script calls to the @{B}USER SCRIPTS@{UB} Menu.
     See @{" AddUserScript " LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/AddUserScript"}

   * Added the following Classes to the General directory:
     @{" DependencyTransformer "  LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/DependencyTransformerClass"}

     @{" Model "                  LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/ModelClass"}
       @{" ValueModel "           LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/ValueModelClass"}
         @{" ComputedValue "      LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/ComputedValueClass"}
           @{" BlockValue "       LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/BlockValueClass"}
         @{" PluggableAdaptor "   LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/PluggableAdaptorClass"}
         @{" ProtocolAdaptor "    LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/ProtocolAdaptorClass"}
           @{" AspectAdaptor "    LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/AspectAdaptorClass"}
           @{" IndexedAdaptor "   LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/IndexedAdaptorClass"}
             @{" SlotAdaptor "    LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/SlotAdaptorClass"}
         @{" ValueHolder "        LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/ValueHolderClass"}
           @{" BufferedValueHolder " LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/BufferedValueHolderClass"}
      
   * Fixed a minor bug in the @{" C/Parse " LINK "Amigatalk:Help/Amigatalk.guide/ParseHelp"} program that did not allow using @{B}|@{UB}
     inside a Block as a colon variable delimiter.  It did accept @{B}!@{UB}
     but it should have accepted both @{B}|@{UB} and @{B}!@{UB}

   * Fixed another annoying bug in the @{" C/Parse " LINK "Amigatalk:Help/Amigatalk.guide/ParseHelp"} program
     that would interpret #Symbol] as a complete @{" Symbol " LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/SymbolClass"} & not as
     #Symbol ], which is sometimes found at the end of a @" Block " LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/BlockClass"}.
     The Parser would therefore never find the end of the Block &
     call it an error.  This means that #] will NOT be interpreted
     as a Symbol (use @{B}']' asSymbol@{UB} instead).  This bug was also present
     in the interpreter & was fixed.
     
   * Added arc drawing methods to @{" Pen.st " LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/PenClass"}

   * Changed unused primitive 139 to FileClose (see @{" File.st close method " LINK "Amigatalk:Help/GeneralClasses.guide/FileClass"}).

   * Added the @{B}Load Class Source File...@{UB} menuItem.
           
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Version2.4" "V2.4 (released on 02-Sep-2003):"

   For Version 2.4, the following enhancements/bug fixes were
   made:

   * Incorporated the Browser CanDo deck into the program.  CanDo libraries
     are no longer necessary since the Browser is no longer a separate
     program.
        
   * Added the Hooks directory to the distribution.  (Not currently implemented)

   * Linked in the CDDevice Class primitives (Nobody used it, so 
     nobody noticed it was missing).
     
   * Added three new methods to the AmigaTalk Class to control 
     the tracing of bytecodes in order to fix the lack of selective
     tracing (See traceState, traceOn & traceOff methods in 
     AmigaTalk:General/AmigaTalk.st).  Furthermore, some methods in
     General Classes will turn off the Tracing paradigm so that the
     trace file you generate will not be excessively large.  The main
     culprits are @{B}new, new: basicNew & basicNew: @{UB}in Class.st
     This change also necessitated the creation of two new script files
     in the C/ directory (TracerOn, TracerOFF) -- Leave them alone,
     they are used internally!
     
   * eliminated the pseudo variables @{B}smalltalk & amigatalk@{UB}.
     a genuine variable named @{FG SHINE}amigatalk @{FG TEXT}is created in the
     AmigaTalk:C/InitializeCommands file to take their place.

@ENDNODE

